      {
        "id": "f656a99eb7dd38156a269af4b7d777ee3afaf3f4",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2701,
          "name": "Lukasz Rajewski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.rajewski@t-mobile.pl",
          "username": "rajewluk"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 07:05:34.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nMost of it is fine because we do not use atm. But in fact some parameters could be used to populate data to AAI if we consider i.e. the day 2 configuration with APPC (Ansible, Netconf). But if we don't then we can leave it like that atm.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "7ad0d3629349c92774f84e6abacf630a062ae2d5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5550,
          "name": "Konrad Banka",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "kbanka.os@gmail.com",
          "username": "kbanka"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 07:08:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Most of it is fine because we do not use atm. But in fact some\n > parameters could be used to populate data to AAI if we consider\n > i.e. the day 2 configuration with APPC (Ansible, Netconf). But if\n > we don't then we can leave it like that atm.\n\nCould you name some examples of such data we could later provide to AAI? Please note that \"IP Addresses\" are internal for ovn networks and can't be used to determine way to \"access\" instantiated workload.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "3fa677bb4f89fbabbf07c400cb432f5bf3250a56",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2701,
          "name": "Lukasz Rajewski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.rajewski@t-mobile.pl",
          "username": "rajewluk"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 07:23:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nour current synchronization with AAI is very limited. Also the support of CNF in AAI is not the final one. But in order to use APPC configuration properly we need to have vserver and vnfc objects created with proper data. Most of the parameters removed (identifiers, naming code), if they were really assigned, could be used to populate this data to AAI somehow. But if we don't think about the APPC in the next release we can forget about it because CDS will take proper data from mdsal.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "34f4189b93541a019f8eedf30f19cb4520cb9dc5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5550,
          "name": "Konrad Banka",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "kbanka.os@gmail.com",
          "username": "kbanka"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 07:36:44.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> our current synchronization with AAI is very limited. Also the\n > support of CNF in AAI is not the final one. But in order to use\n > APPC configuration properly we need to have vserver and vnfc\n > objects created with proper data. Most of the parameters removed\n > (identifiers, naming code), if they were really assigned, could be\n > used to populate this data to AAI somehow. But if we don't think\n > about the APPC in the next release we can forget about it because\n > CDS will take proper data from mdsal.\n\nok, thanks for explaining that. For vserver - this is something that k8splugin is about to populate itself. Not sure about vnfc, but as you say, I'm planning to evolve use-case toward single controller (CDS) instead of adding APPC to it, so probably it's safe to throw them away (at least for now).",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "9b0d38c4644f43cfb4b49895b441db4e0dd4720d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2701,
          "name": "Lukasz Rajewski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.rajewski@t-mobile.pl",
          "username": "rajewluk"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 07:44:41.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nplugin is not able to populate all the information necessary also into vserver because such is use case specific and in fact can be handled only in the blueprint: oam ip address, specific information about network interfaces. So far all the use cases try to keep both controllers. there is no decision about the controllers yet, however we can see that CDS may do more and better. Anyway, for me assumption that we keep CDS only is fine. Would be good to knoe what is the scope of work T-mobile does with Tech Mihindra about Day2 configuration of CNFs with CDS - becuase they initially had such plans for R6.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
